{{Infobox musical artist | name = Julije Bajamonti | image = juliobajamonti.jpg | alt = | caption = Julije Bajamonti | image_size = 100 <!--DO NOT ENLARGE; ORIGINAL RESOLUTION IS THIS --> | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_date = {{Birth date|1744|08|04}} |birth_place =[[Split (city)|Split]], [[Venetian Republic]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1800|11|04|1744|08|04}} |death_place =[[Split (city)|Split]], [[Habsburg Monarchy]] | origin = | instrument = | genre = [[Opera]] | occupation = medical historian, writer, translator, encyclopedist, historian, philosopher, musician | years_active = | label = | associated_acts = | website = }} '''Julije (Julio) Bajamonti''' ([[Italian language|Italian]]: ''Giulio Bajamonti''; 4 August 1744 &ndash; 12 November 1800) was a medical historian, writer, translator, encyclopedist, historian, philosopher, and musician<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UUG0AAAAIAAJ&q=Julije+Bajamonti&dq=Julije+Bajamonti&client=safari&cd=2 Music in Croatia] by Josip Andreis</ref> from the city of [[Split (city)|Split]] in present-day [[Croatia]]. His wife was Ljuba Bajamonti, a Split commoner.
Bajamonti is known for composing the first opera in modern Croatia (''La traslazione di San Doimo'', performed only once), writing about the history of [[Split (city)|Split]] (unfinished and unpublished, and helping [[Alberto Fortis]], a Venetian, with his journey around [[Dalmatia]], which also included the discovery of the now famous South Slavic Muslim song, Hasanaginica.
After the fall of [[Venice]] in 1797 he urged that Dalmatia should be annexed to the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]. In his speech in 1797 he stated that Austria was the successor of the old Venetian state. Like many other intellectuals along the Dalmatian coast, Bajamonti wrote most of his works in Italian. [[Niccolò Tommaseo]] claims that there was no one in Italy who wrote better than Bajamonti during his time.
He performed his medical work in the cities of Split, [[Hvar]], and [[Kotor]] (in the area of Boka Kotorska in today's Montenegro).<ref>[http://www.slowaymusic.com/loader.php?section=skladatelj&page=main&subsect=bio&id=51&lang=en SlowayMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716092850/http://www.slowaymusic.com/loader.php?section=skladatelj&page=main&subsect=bio&id=51&lang=en |date=2011-07-16 }}</ref>
